Installing last versions java and gradle:

Get a Centos 8

1 -- Install java first:  sudo dnf install java-11-openjdk-devel
	And check if is installed:  java -version
2 -- Get it into your path: 
	sudo vi /etc/profile.d/java.sh
		JAVA_HOME="/usr/lib/jvm/java-11-openjdk"
	source /etc/profile.d/java.sh
3 -- Check that works: echo $JAVA_HOME

4 -- Download last Gradle version:
	wget https://services.gradle.org/distributions/gradle-7.5.1-bin.zip


5 -- Create,move,unzip:
	sudo mkdir /opt/gradle
	sudo mv gradle-7.5.1-bin.zip /opt/gradle/
	sudo unzip gradle-7.5.1-bin.zip 

6 -- Add it into your path:
	sudo vi /etc/profile
		export PATH=$PATH:/opt/gradle/gradle-7.5.1/bin
	source /etc/profile
	
7 -- Check that works:
	gradle -v 

8 -- Create a folder for your project:
	mkdir ~/my-project
	cd ~/my-project

9 -- Gradle Wrapper: Create a new build in the new directory:
	gradle init  --> you have to run this the first time, this will create several files.

	gradle wrapper --> once you ran gradle init you can run this command, no idea what this does.


10 -- Run: 
	./gradlew build  --> again, no f. idea what I'm doing.
	

11 -- Create a build. This haven't worked. Create the file build.gradle in the root of the folder's
project and paste this (the build logic):

	task sayHello << {
	println 'Hello, World'
}

task anotherTask << {
	println 'This is another task'
}

UPDATE: The build.gradle is in: my-project/app




